<DOC><DOCNO> AP880507-0203 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0550EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Disasters-Glance     05-07 0300</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Disasters-Glance,0316</SECOND><HEAD>Sorting Through Wreckage of Explosions and Fires</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Industrial Accidents Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are developments Friday in the aftermath ofthe fiery disasters in three cities that killed at least six peoplethis week:</TEXT><TEXT>   REFINERY BLAST   In Norco, La., workers searched the ruins of a Shell Oil Co.refinery, looking for four men still missing since explosionsThursday killed three and injured 42. The bodies of two workerswere found earlier Friday.   Small fires fed by oil and gas residue in the tangle of pipesand equipment still burned in the blast area.   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration and theEnvironmental Protection Agency sent investigators to the plant.</TEXT><TEXT>   SKYSCRAPER FIRE   In Los Angeles, a city councilman said he will propose a lawrequiring automatic fire sprinklers in all city high-risesfollowing Thursday's fire in the 62-story First Interstate Banktower that killed one person and injured 40.   First Interstate officials discounted speculation that word ofpending layoffs in the company division on the floor where the firebroke out could have prompted arson.   City fire officials had yet to determine the cause of the blazethat caused $450 million in damage. Federal investigators from theBureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms were taking part in theinvestigation.</TEXT><TEXT>   PLANT BLAST   In Henderson, Nev., city officials met with executives fromKerr-McGee Corp., which also makes the rocket fuel manufactured atthe now-leveled Pacific Engineering and Production Co. plant.Kerr-McGee, located a mile from the blast site, shut down Thursday,saying they will not reopen until they know more about the accident.   Damage estimates topped $100 million from the explosionsWednesday that killed two people. Nearly a third of the city's16,000 homeowners had already filed damage claims by Friday.</TEXT></DOC>